n	One of four seasons, traditionally the second, marked by the longest and typically hottest days of the year due to the inclination of the Earth and thermal lag. Typically regarded as being from June 21 to September 22 or 23 in parts of the USA, the months of June, July and August in the United Kingdom and the months of December, January and February in the Southern Hemisphere. ; n	(poetic or humorous) year; used to give the age of a person, usually a young one. ; n	(countable, fashion) Someone with light, pinkish skin that has a blue undertone, light hair and eyes, seen as best suited to certain colors of clothing. ; v	(intransitive) To spend the summer, as in a particular place on holiday. ; n	(architecture) A horizontal beam supporting a building. ; n	(obsolete) A pack-horse. ; n	A person who sums. ; n	A machine or algorithm that sums. ; n	(countable) A female given name from English of modern usage, from summer, the name of the season, often given to girls born in summer. ; n	(countable) A surname.
n	(cytology) A large membrane-bound vesicle in a cell's cytoplasm. ; n	A small empty or air-filled space or vacuity.

n	Traditionally the fourth of the four seasons, typically regarded as being from December 23 to March 20 in continental regions of the Northern Hemisphere or the months of June, July, and August in the Southern Hemisphere. It is the time when the sun is lowest in the sky, resulting in short days, and the time of year with the lowest atmospheric temperatures for the region. ; n	(figuratively, poetic) The period of decay, old age, death, or the like. ; n	(countable, fashion) Someone with dark skin, eyes and hair, seen as best suited to certain colors of clothing. ; n	(obsolete) An appliance to be fixed on the front of a grate, to keep a kettle warm, etc. ; n	(India, archaic) The rainy season. ; v	(intransitive) To spend the winter (in a particular place). ; v	(transitive) To store something (for instance animals) somewhere over winter to protect it from cold. ; n	(countable) A surname from the Germanic languages. ; n	(countable) A unisex given name ; n	An unincorporated community in Senlac Rural Municipality No. 411, Saskatchewan, Canada. ; n	An unincorporated community in Putnam County, West Virginia, United States. ; n	A small town and village in Sawyer County, Wisconsin, United States. ; n	The personification of winter, wintertime ; n	(poetry) Alternative form of winter [Traditionally the fourth of the four seasons, typically regarded as being from December 23 to March 20 in continental regions of the Northern Hemisphere or the months of June, July, and August in the Southern Hemisphere.
